          "body": "The chapter's first major saying (8:12) must be heard against the festival just concluded. Each night of Tabernacles, four great golden lampstands were lit in the Court of the Women — so brightly, the Mishnah says (*Sukkah* 5.3), that 'there was no courtyard in Jerusalem that was not lit by the light of the place of water-drawing.' Standing in that very court at dawn, with the lampstands extinguished, Jesus declares: *I* am the Light of the world. The ceremonial light was a sign; He is the substance. The follower of Christ does not walk in *skotia* (the same word of John 1:5) but has the Light *of life* — light that is itself life, the same identification John makes in the prologue (1:4). The claim is staggering in its setting."
